.TH _PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Holberton School" "_printf Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom formatted output conversion function
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output according to a format string.  
It writes to the standard output (stdout) and behaves similarly to the
standard C library function printf(3), but supports only a limited set 
of conversion specifiers as required by the Holberton School project.

The format string may contain ordinary characters, which are written 
unchanged, and conversion specifiers beginning with the '%' character.

This implementation supports the following conversion specifiers:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string.  
If the string is NULL, "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %%
Prints the '%' character.

.TP
.B %d
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B %i
Prints a signed decimal integer (identical to %d).

.PP
This implementation does NOT handle:
.IP \(bu 2
Flags (+, space, #, -, 0)
.IP \(bu
Field width
.IP \(bu
Precision
.IP \(bu
Length modifiers (l, h, etc.)
.IP \(bu
Other specifiers such as %u, %o, %x, %X, %p

.SH RETURN VALUE
The function returns the total number of characters printed.  
If the format string is NULL, the function returns -1.

.SH ERROR HANDLING
.IP \(bu 2
Unknown specifiers are printed literally (example: "%q" â†’ "%q")
.IP \(bu
Returns -1 when format is NULL

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Hello World!\n");

_printf("Character: %c\n", 'A');

_printf("String: %s\n", "Holberton");

_printf("Percent: %%\n");

_printf("Integer: %d\n", 123);

_printf("Negative: %i\n", -456);
.fi

.SH CONFORMING TO
This implementation follows the specifications of the Holberton School
group project "0x11. C - printf".  
It uses:
.IP \(bu 2
write() for output
.IP \(bu
Variadic functions from stdarg.h
.IP \(bu
No global variables
.IP \(bu
Betty coding style

.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3), write(2), stdarg(3)

.SH AUTHOR
Developed by Bryan Ramos and Cristian Acevedo
